#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
MKT Christ — Micah chapter 7 (all 20 verses missing)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-micah-7-7-full.py

Key Christological connections:
- 7:1 no first-ripe fig → Matt 21:19 (cursed fig tree, no fruit)
- 7:2 none upright → Rom 3:10-12 (universal sinfulness)
- 7:6 man's enemies = household → Matt 10:35-36 (Jesus quotes directly)
- 7:7 wait/watch for YHWH → Heb 12:2 (fix eyes on Jesus)
- 7:8 fall and rise, darkness → 1 Cor 15:54-57; John 8:12
- 7:9 bear indignation, brought to light → 2 Cor 5:21 (sin-bearer)
- 7:14 shepherd with staff → John 10:11 (good shepherd)
- 7:18-19 who is a God like you, sins into the sea → Col 2:13-14; 1 John 4:9-10
- 7:20 faithfulness to Abraham → Gal 3:16 (seed = Christ)
"""

import json
from pathlib import Path

ROOT = Path(__file__).resolve().parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

MICAH = {
    "7": {
        "1": '<p class="christ-allusion">Micah laments that he has &quot;become like one who after the summer fruit has been gathered... finds no first-ripe fig that my soul desires.&quot; The absent fig — the covenant community bare of faithful people — is the condition Jesus enacts as judgment when he curses the fig tree that has leaves but no fruit (Matt 21:19). The fig tree withers because it offers only the form of vitality without the substance. Micah laments the fruitlessness; Jesus judges it. The one who desires first-ripe figs and finds none is also the one who, encountering Israel&apos;s religious establishment in full leaf, names and enacts the verdict Micah anticipated.</p>',
        "2": '<p class="christ-theme">The universal diagnosis — &quot;The godly has perished from the earth; there is no one upright among mankind; they all lie in wait for blood, and each hunts the other with a net&quot; — is the specific condition Paul describes in Romans 3:10-12 as the universal human situation: &quot;None is righteous, no, not one; no one understands; no one seeks for God. All have turned aside; together they have become worthless.&quot; Paul&apos;s catena from the Psalms and prophets reaches its point: all alike stand under the same need for the righteousness that comes through faith in Christ (Rom 3:22). Micah&apos;s historical lament becomes Paul&apos;s anthropological axiom, the premise that makes the gospel necessary.</p>',
        "3": '<p class="christ-theme">The hands of the prince, judge, and great man all stretched out to do evil — corruption at every level of the social order — describes the principalities and powers that crucified the Lord of glory (1 Cor 2:8). Both hands doing evil for a bribe is the condition that delivered Jesus to the cross: Judas for thirty pieces of silver, the chief priests for fear of losing status, Pilate for political expediency. What Micah diagnoses as Israel&apos;s social disease, the passion narrative dramatizes as the mechanism of the crucifixion. Christ enters the worst of what Micah describes and transforms it from within.</p>',
        "4": '<p class="christ-allusion">The best of the community being &quot;like a brier, the most upright of them a thorn hedge&quot; is the OT form of Jesus&apos;s question: &quot;Are grapes gathered from thornbushes, or figs from thistles?&quot; (Matt 7:16). The test of genuine covenant membership is fruit: what a person produces reveals what they are. Micah finds nothing but thorns at the top of the social hierarchy; Jesus teaches that thorns and thistles reveal the false prophet, the bad tree. The Christological resolution: he who bore the thorns as a crown (John 19:2) transforms those who are in him into fruit-bearing branches (John 15:5).</p>',
        "5": '<p class="christ-allusion">The warning not to trust a neighbor, to guard one&apos;s mouth even with the wife of one&apos;s bosom, describes the radical breakdown of relational trust that characterizes a society where covenant has collapsed. Jesus radicalizes rather than softens this: &quot;Do not think that I have come to bring peace to the earth. I have not come to bring peace, but a sword&quot; (Matt 10:34). The fractures Micah laments in a covenant-breaking community, Jesus announces as the cost of genuine covenant allegiance in a divided world. Trust is restored only in the community gathered around him.</p>',
        "6": '<p class="christ-direct">Micah 7:6 is directly quoted by Jesus in Matthew 10:35-36 and Luke 12:53: &quot;a man&apos;s enemies are the men of his own household.&quot; In Micah, the household fracture is a symptom of covenant disintegration. In Jesus&apos;s teaching, it becomes the expected social cost of the kingdom&apos;s arrival — loyalty to Christ creates divisions within households that have not yet come to him. What Micah mourns as the worst symptom of Israel&apos;s unfaithfulness, Jesus cites as the sociological result of his own coming. He does not apologize for the division; he names it as the necessary consequence of the word of God entering a resistant world.</p>',
        "7": '<p class="christ-theme">Micah&apos;s declaration — &quot;But as for me, I will watch expectantly for YHWH; I will wait for the God of my salvation; my God will hear me&quot; — is the posture of faith in the face of covenant collapse. Hebrews 12:2 names this posture&apos;s fulfillment: &quot;looking to Jesus, the founder and perfecter of our faith, who for the joy that was set before him endured the cross, despising the shame, and is seated at the right hand of the throne of God.&quot; Micah watches; Jesus is the one toward whom watching is directed. The patient expectation the prophet models is given its object and its guarantee in Christ, who himself endured by watching the Father&apos;s faithfulness.</p>',
        "8": '<p class="christ-type">The covenant confession — &quot;when I fall, I shall rise; when I sit in darkness, YHWH will be a light to me&quot; — is the OT pattern of descent and ascent that Christ enacts definitively. He falls in death; he rises in resurrection (1 Cor 15:20). He sits in the darkness of the grave; he becomes the light of the world (John 8:12). The pattern Micah articulates as faith — the expectation that falling is not the final word — is enacted by Christ as history: the actual falling into death and the actual rising that makes the pattern not just possible but accomplished. Those in Christ receive the pattern as their own: &quot;Death is swallowed up in victory&quot; (1 Cor 15:54).</p>',
        "9": '<p class="christ-type">Micah&apos;s confession — &quot;I will bear the indignation of YHWH because I have sinned against him, until he pleads my cause and executes judgment for me. He will bring me out to the light; I shall look upon his vindication (<em>tzidqato</em>)&quot; — is a type of Christ&apos;s substitutionary bearing of divine judgment. Paul states what Micah&apos;s pattern anticipates: &quot;For our sake he made him to be sin who knew no sin, so that in him we might become the righteousness of God&quot; (2 Cor 5:21). Christ bore the indignation without having sinned, so that his vindication (<em>dikaiosis</em>) becomes ours. He was &quot;delivered up for our trespasses and raised for our justification&quot; (Rom 4:25) — brought to the light so that we look upon his righteousness and receive it.</p>',
        "10": '<p class="christ-theme">The enemy&apos;s shame when she sees YHWH&apos;s vindication — &quot;Where is YHWH your God?&quot; becoming her covering of shame — anticipates the silencing of every accusation Paul describes: &quot;Who shall bring any charge against God&apos;s elect? It is God who justifies. Who is to condemn? Christ Jesus is the one who died — more than that, who was raised — who is at the right hand of God, who indeed is interceding for us&quot; (Rom 8:33-34). The enemy who taunted God&apos;s people is answered by the resurrection: the question &quot;Where is your God?&quot; receives the answer &quot;Risen, interceding, reigning.&quot;</p>',
        "11": '<p class="christ-allusion">The day when walls are rebuilt and boundaries far extended — the expansion of the covenant community beyond its former limits — anticipates Paul&apos;s announcement that &quot;he himself is our peace, who has made us both one and has broken down in his flesh the dividing wall of hostility&quot; (Eph 2:14). The wall that divided Jew from Gentile, covenant from non-covenant, is broken down by the cross. The expanded boundary of Micah&apos;s restoration — the new walls of a rebuilt city embracing more than before — reaches its fulfillment in the inclusive covenant community gathered from every nation in Christ.</p>',
        "12": '<p class="christ-allusion">The universal pilgrimage — &quot;In that day they will come to you, from Assyria and the cities of Egypt... from sea to sea and mountain to mountain&quot; — is the OT vision of the nations streaming to Zion. Revelation 7:9 shows its fulfillment: &quot;a great multitude that no one could number, from every nation, from all tribes and peoples and languages, standing before the throne and before the Lamb.&quot; The geography of the gathering expands from the ancient near east to every corner of the globe. Christ is the gathering point — the throne and the Lamb before whom the pilgrimage ends and the worship begins.</p>',
        "13": '<p class="christ-theme">The earth&apos;s desolation because of its inhabitants&apos; deeds — the consequence of persistent covenant violation — is the backdrop against which Christ&apos;s new creation work is set. Peter describes the same horizon: the present heavens and earth are stored up for fire, reserved for judgment (2 Pet 3:7). But beyond judgment: &quot;we are waiting for new heavens and a new earth in which righteousness dwells&quot; (2 Pet 3:13). Micah&apos;s desolation is not the last word; Christ&apos;s resurrection is the first-fruit of the new creation that will replace what judgment removes (Rev 21:1).</p>',
        "14": '<p class="christ-allusion">The prayer — &quot;Shepherd your people with your staff, the flock of your inheritance, who dwell alone in a forest in the midst of a garden land; let them graze in Bashan and Gilead as in the days of old&quot; — invokes the shepherd-king image that Jesus fulfills directly: &quot;I am the good shepherd. The good shepherd lays down his life for the sheep&quot; (John 10:11). The staff (<em>shevet</em>, also a royal scepter) is the instrument of both protection and authority. Jesus wields both — protecting his flock by his death and ruling it by his resurrection. The pasture he leads the flock to is not Bashan and Gilead but the abundant life he himself provides (John 10:10).</p>',
        "15": '<p class="christ-allusion">The petition &quot;Show us marvelous things (<em>niflaot</em>) as in the days when you came out of Egypt&quot; — invoking the Exodus as the paradigm of divine wonder-working — is answered in Christ, who &quot;was attested to you by God with mighty works and wonders and signs that God did through him in your midst&quot; (Acts 2:22). The Exodus miracles are the type; the miracles of Jesus are the antitype. More than that: his resurrection is the definitive miracle beyond all Exodus signs — not rescue from Egypt but rescue from death itself. John&apos;s Gospel presents Jesus&apos;s signs as the manifestation of his glory (John 2:11), fulfilling the prayer for divine wonders.</p>',
        "16": '<p class="christ-allusion">The nations seeing YHWH&apos;s marvelous deeds and being ashamed of all their might — &quot;they shall lay their hands on their mouths; their ears shall be deaf&quot; — anticipates the eschatological silencing that the gospel creates: every mouth stopped, the whole world accountable to God (Rom 3:19). The nations&apos; mighty acts are exposed as nothing before YHWH&apos;s acts. Christ&apos;s resurrection is the decisive wonder before which all alternative powers fall silent — the wisdom of the world made foolish, the strength of the world made weakness (1 Cor 1:20-25).</p>',
        "17": '<p class="christ-allusion">The nations coming trembling from their strongholds, &quot;like snakes licking the dust&quot; — the comprehensive submission of hostile powers — anticipates the universal acclamation Paul envisions: &quot;at the name of Jesus every knee should bow, in heaven and on earth and under the earth, and every tongue confess that Jesus Christ is Lord&quot; (Phil 2:10-11). The trembling posture Micah describes as the nations&apos; response to YHWH&apos;s wonders becomes in Philippians the posture of universal submission to the exalted name. What the nations do in reversal of their pride, every creature will do in the eschatological acknowledgment of Christ&apos;s sovereignty.</p>',
        "18": '<p class="christ-type">The doxological question — &quot;Who is a God like you (<em>mi-el kamocha</em>), pardoning iniquity and passing over transgression for the remnant of his inheritance? He does not retain his anger forever, because he delights in steadfast love (<em>hesed</em>)&quot; — is answered in the incarnation and atonement. God demonstrates that he is precisely this kind of God in Christ: &quot;God shows his love for us in that while we were still sinners, Christ died for us&quot; (Rom 5:8). The hesed that Micah declares is God&apos;s delight becomes in Paul the demonstration of that love in the gift of the Son. The question &quot;Who is a God like you?&quot; receives its definitive answer in the cross: the God who pardons by providing the propitiation himself (1 John 4:10).</p>',
        "19": '<p class="christ-direct">The promise that YHWH will &quot;tread our iniquities underfoot&quot; and &quot;cast all our sins into the depths of the sea&quot; is enacted at the cross. Paul declares: &quot;And you, who were dead in your trespasses... God made alive together with him, having forgiven us all our trespasses, by canceling the record of debt that stood against us with its legal demands. This he set aside, nailing it to the cross&quot; (Col 2:13-14). The casting-into-the-sea is accomplished by Christ bearing the full weight of the debt himself and removing it — not merely covering but eliminating. Hebrews adds: &quot;he appeared once for all at the end of the ages to put away sin by the sacrifice of himself&quot; (Heb 9:26).</p>',
        "20": '<p class="christ-direct">The final verse appeals to the sworn covenant: &quot;You will show faithfulness (<em>emet</em>) to Jacob and steadfast love (<em>hesed</em>) to Abraham, as you have sworn to our fathers from the days of old.&quot; Paul identifies the specific heir through whom this sworn faithfulness is fulfilled: &quot;the promises were made to Abraham and to his offspring. It does not say, &apos;And to offsprings,&apos; referring to many, but referring to one, &apos;And to your offspring,&apos; who is Christ&quot; (Gal 3:16). The oath YHWH swore from days of old is kept in the one Seed who is Christ. Micah&apos;s closing appeal to the covenant oath is answered by the resurrection of the one in whom all the promises of God find their Yes and Amen (2 Cor 1:20).</p>'
    }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'micah')
    merge_comm(existing, MICAH)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'micah', existing)
    print('Micah 7 mkt-christ written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
